<subSubSection id="C30E65693F786D4DFCA1FF6EFC4AFB81" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BAB36E23F786D4DFCA1FF6EFC4AFB81" blockId="9.[809,1422,246,1088]" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">
During this survey, a single specimen (DM 13218) of this species was netted over water in old growth forest at Bentor, Liberian Nimba. The dorsal pelage of the specimen is cinnamon-brown which extends onto the head. The ventral pelage is light silvery-grey. Both dorsal and ventral hairs have darker bases. There is no flank or dorsal stripe, or dots present on the bat. The wing membrane is medium brown without reticulation; however from dorsal view, there appeared to be obvious bright orange-red markings on the wing (
<figureCitation id="132F2A673F786D4DFBAFFDD2FB62FDA5" box="[1089,1186,586,612]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="10.[151,164,1397,1418]" captionTargetBox="[151,763,174,1375]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,765,173,1033]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIG. 3. Image of the Glauconycteris cf. argentata specimen (DM 13218) captured at Bentor, Liberian Mt Nimba, showing: A — the distinct orange-red markings on the upper wing; and B — the tragus" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3942487" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3942487/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
), which completely disappeared in the preserved specimen. The tragus is fairly elongate with the outer margin more curved than that of the inner margin; there is a distinct pointed lobe near the base of the outer margin (
<figureCitation id="132F2A673F786D4DFCDCFD6CFC4FFCCF" box="[818,911,756,782]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="10.[151,164,1397,1418]" captionTargetBox="[151,763,174,1375]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,765,173,1033]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIG. 3. Image of the Glauconycteris cf. argentata specimen (DM 13218) captured at Bentor, Liberian Mt Nimba, showing: A — the distinct orange-red markings on the upper wing; and B — the tragus" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3942487" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3942487/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
). Forearm length is 
<quantity id="4CEC9B073F786D4DFB6DFD6CFB31FCCF" box="[1155,1265,756,782]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.37" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" unit="mm" value="43.7">43.7 mm</quantity>
, and greatest skull length 
<quantity id="4CEC9B073F786D4DFC52FC8EFBE9FCF1" box="[956,1065,790,816]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6199999999999999" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" unit="mm" value="16.2">16.2 mm</quantity>
. We have tentatively assigned this specimen to 
<taxonomicName id="4C144D613F786D4DFBEEFCA0FB5AFC93" baseAuthorityName="Dobson" baseAuthorityYear="1875" box="[1024,1178,824,850]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Glauconycteris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="argentata">
<emphasis id="B960EAF03F786D4DFBEEFCA0FB5AFC93" box="[1024,1178,824,850]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">G. argentata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but caution that it may represent an undescribed species. Although the measurements and pelage fit that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C144D613F786D4DFAF6FCE4FC97FC79" baseAuthorityName="Dobson" baseAuthorityYear="1875" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Glauconycteris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="argentata">
<emphasis id="B960EAF03F786D4DFAF6FCE4FC97FC79" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">G. argentata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the wing membrane differs distinctly by not being pale in colour (
<bibRefCitation id="EF854B133F786D4DFBDAFC58FB37FC1B" author="HAPPOLD, M." box="[1076,1271,960,986]" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" pagination="564 - 566" refId="ref13498" refString="HAPPOLD, M. 2013 a. Glauconycteris argentata Common butterfly bat. Pp. 564 - 566, in The mammals of Africa. Volume IV: Hedgehogs, shrews and bats (M. HAPPOLD and D. C. D. HAPPOLD, eds). Bloomsbury Publishing, London, 800 pp." type="book chapter" year="2013">
Happold, 2013 
<emphasis id="B960EAF03F786D4DFB06FC58FB37FC1B" box="[1256,1271,960,986]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">a</emphasis>
</bibRefCitation>
). It is noteworthy that 
<taxonomicName id="4C144D613F786D4DFC54FC7AFB91FC3D" baseAuthorityName="Dobson" baseAuthorityYear="1875" box="[954,1105,994,1020]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Glauconycteris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="argentata">
<emphasis id="B960EAF03F786D4DFC54FC7AFB91FC3D" box="[954,1105,994,1020]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">G. argentata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has not yet been recorded west of 
<collectingCountry id="F30376723F786D4DFC70FB9CFBDCFBDF" box="[926,1052,1028,1054]" name="Cameroon" pageId="9" pageNumber="368">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
(about 
<quantity id="4CEC9B073F786D4DFB60FB9CFACBFBDF" box="[1166,1291,1028,1054]" metricMagnitude="6" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="368" unit="km" value="2000.0">2,000 km</quantity>
from Mt Nimba).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
